Philadelphia and Allegheny counties strongly in Fetterman's favor. Oz can be expected to gain a good amount of ground as the night continues, I see it improbable that it will be enough as of now.

Sabato just tipped R, which pushes this one further red in my overall estimate. Fetterman once had a huge lead here. The hard right turn in this election was dramatic.
I'm definitely a little bit overconfident on this one objectively. However polls + momentum + candidate quality + national environment + intuition are all pushing in the same direction here.

This has been one of the most interesting races of the midterms from the start. Fetterman (D) is the Lt. Governor of an R+2 state and is running a campaign based on progressive populism and force of personality. Oz (R) is a television star with brand name recognition but no political experience and no real ties to PA other than real estate. Fetterman's campaign more or less stopped in its tracks when he suffered a stroke on the eve of the primaries. He won the nomination, but remained mostly out of public view until recently. He participated in a tv interview and a televised debate, both of which demonstrated he is still in recovery. The debate performance has generally been considered disastrous. There has been skepticism in recent years of the utility of debates and their effect on voters. This debate seems to have moved the needle. Prediction markets shifted dramatically, and polls were already starting to favor Oz after the interview. Whether or not voters will follow suit remains to be seen, but if momentum has shifted, then it hasn't shifted in favor of Fetterman. A crude averaging of the prediction markets, pollsters, and professional forecasters gives Oz an ever so slight advantage of 51-49. Anything can happen, but I think this trend will continue. 55-45, Oz.

This year's Senate races are a lot of the Democrats bringing the best candidates that they can versus some of the worst Republican candidates. While this should be a +3 Republican election, Oz comes off is so deranged that he's throwing the entire moderate vote to the Democrats.

This could have been a race. Now it isn't. If Fetterman doesn't drop dead, he'll win, and might win even if he died. Yes, that's how bad Oz is as a candidate. At a bare minimum, when running for office, a person should be able to definitively answer a question like "How many houses do you own?" the same way twice. It's not too much to ask. Or it is...

This remains the most interesting senate race to me. In terms of actual policy, Fetterman is the most extreme of any Democratic candidate in a competitive race this cycle, as far as I can tell. Oz is pro gay marriage, pro-choice at the federal level, and thinks Joe Biden won 2020, putting him more in line with a Glenn Youngkin than a Doug Mastriano. Typically, moderates beat wing-nuts in elections. The fact that Oz is polling this poorly despite this speaks to his incredibly high personal unfavorables, even among a lot of Republicans. On top of all this you have Fetterman's health issues and refusal to do the normal number and times of debates.

I don't agree with the crowd here or with 538 that this is a tossup. Yes PA is a tossup state, but this race isn't a tossup in my opinion. I know it's a red wave year and Biden is unpopular and all of that, but I think it's a serious possibility that Fetterman wins. He is running a brilliant campaign.
